  <h2 id="what-are-clubs">What Are Cannabis Social Clubs?</h2>

  <p>A cannabis social club in Madrid, formally known as an <em>asociación cannábica</em>, is a private, members-only non-profit association where members collectively cultivate, distribute, and consume cannabis in a shared space. Unlike Amsterdam's famous coffee shops—which operate as licensed, publicly accessible businesses—Madrid's clubs are intentionally exclusive. They're not tourist attractions. They're not advertised on street corners with neon signs. They exist in a legal gray area that exists because of Spain's freedom-of-association laws and the constitutional right to privacy in private spaces.</p>

  <p>The first time you approach a Madrid cannabis club, you won't see much from the street. A small brass plaque, maybe. A buzzer. An unmarked door. This is intentional. Spanish law distinguishes between personal use (decriminalized, not legal) and trafficking (criminal). These clubs operate as private collectives—essentially, you're joining a cooperative where members collectively grow and share cannabis with each other, not a retail business selling to strangers. The legal framework is precarious but has held for decades.</p>

  <h2 id="how-they-work">How They Actually Work</h2>

  <p>Here's the practical side: most clubs operate as non-profit associations registered with the Spanish authorities. Members pay a monthly or yearly membership fee (typically €20-50 per month). This fee goes toward rent, utilities, staff, and the cost of bulk cannabis cultivation. The club then distributes whatever is grown communally among its members at cost—there's no profit motive, at least in theory.</p>

  <p>To become a member, you typically need an introduction from an existing member or you find a club through local networks and contacts. Some clubs are stricter about vetting; others are more relaxed. There's usually paperwork involved—they'll take your ID, have you sign agreements about conduct and consumption rules. They want documentation that shows they're actually a membership association, not a public business, if Spanish authorities ever ask questions.</p>

  <p>Once you're in, the club assigns you a membership number. You can enter any time during operating hours. Some clubs are open 24/7 if they have a small permanent staff; others keep standard hours like a bar (5 PM–2 AM is common). You'll likely get a member card. When you visit, you sign in, maybe pay a small daily consumption fee (€3-10, depending on the club and what you purchase), and then you access the product counter.</p>

  <p>The economics are simple but unusual for what looks like a retail experience. The club pools member fees and cultivation costs into a collective budget. Individual transactions don't generate profit because there's no company taking a cut—it's cost-sharing among members. A gram of flower might cost €8-12, which is roughly what wholesale costs Madrid clubs when they're buying from larger growers or growing it themselves. That's genuinely cheaper than street prices, which is why thousands of Madrid residents maintain club memberships.</p>

  <h2 id="inside-a-club">What It Looks Like Inside</h2>

  <p>Walk through that unmarked door and here's what you'll typically encounter: a small reception area with a desk where someone checks your membership. They log your visit. It's low-key but official. Some clubs have a security person stationed here; others just have staff monitoring who comes and goes. It's not aggressive—more like a nightclub entrance than a police station—but there's always someone making sure you're a member.</p>

  <p>From there, you enter the main lounge. And this is where clubs vary wildly. The small ones—maybe 30-50 regular members—might have a living room setup: a couple of couches, a coffee table, a TV, maybe 20-30 square meters of usable space. The larger ones—500+ members—operate more like bars or clubs. There's actual seating for 100+ people. The lighting is usually warm and dim, designed to feel relaxed and not institutional. Most clubs play music. Some have pool tables. Some have private smoking rooms with ventilation (which are increasingly required by local regulations and club policies). The atmosphere is social but not party-like. You'll see locals, tourists, people working on laptops, groups hanging out.</p>

  <p>The counter or dispensing area is where the products are. Usually it's behind glass or in a locked cabinet, staffed by someone who knows the inventory. When you order, you tell them what you want—"un gramo de Gorilla Glue," "dos porros," "cinco gramos de hachís"—and they weigh it out in front of you in a small bag or rolling paper. You pay cash. Most clubs only accept cash because of banking complications with a federally illegal substance. The transactions are fast, anonymous, and straightforward.</p>

  <p>The bathrooms are usually functional, sometimes clean, sometimes not. Ventilation varies. Many larger clubs have invested in better HVAC because secondhand smoke complaints from neighbors are a real problem. A few clubs have actually been shut down by police or by neighborhood pressure. When you're visiting, the quality of the space tells you something about the club's long-term stability and professionalism.</p>

  <p>Some clubs have food and drink service. You might find beer, soft drinks, coffee, and snacks available. A few have full kitchens and serve actual meals. Others explicitly say no outside food or drinks. It depends on the club and their relationship with local authorities. The more commercial the setup, the more risk—which is why many clubs keep things deliberately spare.</p>

