  <h2 id="not-amsterdam">Why Madrid Is Not Amsterdam</h2>

  <div class="comparison-box">
    <h3>Madrid Clubs vs Amsterdam Coffee Shops</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Madrid:</strong> Private membership associations. Amsterdam: Licensed retail businesses.</li>
      <li><strong>Madrid:</strong> You need to know someone or find them through networks. Amsterdam: Walk in from the street.</li>
      <li><strong>Madrid:</strong> More exclusive, less touristy, less commercialized. Amsterdam: Designed for tourists, heavily branded, widely advertised.</li>
      <li><strong>Madrid:</strong> No standardization—each club operates independently with its own culture and rules. Amsterdam: Regulated, consistent standards, official licensing.</li>
      <li><strong>Madrid:</strong> Prices are genuine cost-sharing, slightly cheaper. Amsterdam: Retail markup, more expensive.</li>
      <li><strong>Madrid:</strong> Legal status is ambiguous but tolerated. Amsterdam: Fully legal, taxed, inspected.</li>
      <li><strong>Madrid:</strong> You'll encounter mostly Spanish locals. Amsterdam: Mostly tourists.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>Amsterdam's coffee shops are legal, licensed businesses where you can walk in as a stranger and order cannabis like you would at a café. The Dutch government regulates them, taxes them, and treats them as legitimate commerce. Cannabis is sold, not "distributed among members." The experience is open, tourist-friendly, and commercialized.</p>

  <p>Madrid clubs are the opposite. They're private collectives in a legal gray zone, operating under the assumption that members collectively growing and sharing cannabis is protected by Spain's freedom-of-association laws. The Spanish government doesn't license them; they're not officially recognized. They exist because enforcement is selective and resources are limited. It's a different beast entirely.</p>

  <p>This has practical implications. Amsterdam coffee shops sometimes feel clinical or overly touristy—you're buying cannabis from a business, lines can be long, the atmosphere is transactional. Madrid clubs feel more social and relaxed, but they're also less transparent and less guaranteed to still exist next month. Amsterdam shops have predictable hours and consistent rules. Some Madrid clubs are casual about their operations; others are locked down tighter than you'd expect.</p>

  <p>For tourists, the Madrid experience is less obviously "cannabis tourism" and more like you've been invited into a local space. That's the appeal. You're not a customer; you're a guest at a member association. It feels more authentic, more cultural, less like you're at a chain store. The trade-off is that you need access, knowledge, and social navigation to get in the door.</p>

  <h2 id="club-culture">Club Culture & Etiquette</h2>

  <p>Every Madrid club has its own culture, but there are unwritten rules that most follow. First: respect the space and the people in it. Don't be loud or aggressive. Don't try to bring non-members in without asking first. Don't steal or cause drama. Clubs that have been operating for years have survived because they maintain a low profile and handle problems internally.</p>

  <p>Second: follow the club's specific rules. Some clubs let you smoke anywhere. Others have designated smoking areas or require you to use a smoking room. Some explicitly prohibit alcohol-fueled behavior. A few clubs are stricter and will ask you to leave if you're too intoxicated or disruptive. Read the posted rules when you arrive; every club has them, usually in Spanish and sometimes in English.</p>

  <p>Third: respect other members. Don't approach people and try to sell them things or make sketchy deals. Clubs actively discourage internal trafficking because it attracts police attention. If you want to buy or sell privately, do it outside the club. Inside, the assumption is that everyone is there as a member, and transactions happen through the official counter.</p>

  <p>Fourth: if you're a guest of a member, you're their responsibility. If you cause problems, your sponsor loses membership or gets a warning. This system is actually quite effective at policing behavior because members vouching for you creates social accountability.</p>

  <p>Fifth: don't take photos without permission. Many clubs explicitly forbid it. Some allow it in lounges but not at the counter. Others are fine with it anywhere. It depends on the club's risk tolerance. Ask first. Respect the answer.</p>

  <p>The atmosphere in most clubs is genuinely welcoming, especially to international visitors. Spanish people are social, and cannabis clubs are social spaces. You'll have conversations with locals, exchange recommendations, maybe make friends. It's one of the few places in Madrid where tourists and residents genuinely mix in a non-transactional way.</p>

  <h2 id="what-is-available">Products & Menus</h2>

  <p>What's actually available in a Madrid cannabis club varies by the club's supply chain and growing partnerships. Most clubs stock the following:</p>

  <p><strong>Flower (cogollos):</strong> This is the dried, cured cannabis bud. Most clubs have 3-8 varieties available at any given time, ranging from "basic" or "economy" strains (often Indica-heavy, more sedating, €8-10/g) to premium cultivars with exotic names (Gelato, Wedding Cake, Jack Herer, €12-15/g). Quality varies. Some clubs pride themselves on small-batch, high-quality cultivation. Others are just moving volume. Look at the buds—they should be dense, well-trimmed, and smell fresh. If it looks brown and dusty, it's old or low-quality.</p>

  <p><strong>Hash (hachís):</strong> This is cannabis resin, usually imported from North Africa (Morocco) or produced locally. It comes in small blocks or crumbles. Quality ranges from cheap and barely psychoactive (€4-6/g) to premium hand-pressed hash that's expensive and potent (€12-18/g). Hash has a longer shelf life than flower and is very popular in Spain. Many clubs have 2-4 varieties available.</p>

  <p><strong>Pre-rolled joints (porros):</strong> Ready-to-smoke joints, usually made with a mix of flower and hash. Clubs prepare these for convenience. Prices are €2-5 depending on size and quality. They're popular with people who want immediate consumption without rolling their own.</p>

  <p><strong>Edibles:</strong> Not all clubs have them, but it's increasingly common to find brownies, cookies, gummies, or other infused products. These are usually made in-house or sourced from trusted producers. Prices vary widely (€3-10 per unit), and potency labeling is often non-existent or unclear, so ask questions.</p>

  <p><strong>Concentrates:</strong> Waxes, shatter, live resin, and distillates are becoming more common in larger clubs. These are high-THC products, often extracted from trim or flower using solvents or ice. Prices are €15-30/gram depending on type and quality. They require special equipment to consume (dabbing rig or vaporizer).</p>

  <p><strong>Supplies:</strong> Most clubs sell rolling papers, filters, grinders, and maybe lighters. Some sell bongs or pipes. A few have vaporizers for sale. These are convenience items, not the core of their business.</p>

  <p>The menu changes based on what's in stock. Popular clubs with reliable supply have consistent variety. Smaller clubs might have only 2-3 options available. During harvest seasons (spring and autumn in most grow operations), variety increases and prices sometimes drop slightly due to abundance. If you have preferences, ask the staff—they know what's good and what to recommend.</p>

  <h2 id="choosing-a-club">Picking the Right Club for You</h2>

  <p>Not every club is right for every person. Here's how to think about it:</p>

  <p><strong>Atmosphere:</strong> Do you want a bar-like social environment or a quieter lounge? Visit during different times of day and see how the vibe changes. Evening clubs are busier; afternoons are more relaxed. Some clubs are full of tourists making noise; others are mostly local residents in a calm space.</p>

  <p><strong>Size and Cleanliness:</strong> Small clubs feel more personal but can be cramped and poorly ventilated. Large clubs feel professional but can be less intimate. Check the bathrooms, the air quality, and the general cleanliness. These reflect the club's standards and longevity. If a place smells terrible and looks run-down, it probably won't be around in six months.</p>

  <p><strong>Product Quality and Variety:</strong> Ask staff what strains they have and ask to see them before buying. Quality varies wildly between clubs. Some are genuinely proud of their product; others just want your money. Talk to other members about their experience. Ask what's consistent, what's inconsistent, what's worth buying.</p>

  <p><strong>Price:</strong> There's not huge variation (most clubs charge similar amounts), but some offer better discounts for larger purchases or membership packages. Compare before committing to a membership.</p>

  <p><strong>Location and Accessibility:</strong> A club near your accommodation is convenient. But don't choose based on location alone if the product or atmosphere is poor. Being 20 minutes away is worth it if the club is genuinely better.</p>

  <p><strong>Staff Knowledge:</strong> Good clubs have staff who actually know the products—they can tell you the difference between strains, the effects, the growing methods. Indifferent staff just hand you whatever you ask for and disappear. Knowledge is a sign of professionalism.</p>

  <p><strong>Safety and Vibe:</strong> Does the club feel safe? Are there security measures? Does the staff seem professional? Are members being respectful to each other? Trust your instinct. If a place feels sketchy, it probably is.</p>

  <p>The best way to find a good club is honestly through word-of-mouth. Ask locals, other tourists, or staff at your accommodation. Avoid clubs that aggressively recruit you on the street—those are usually not the high-quality ones. The best clubs rely on reputation and member referrals, not street promotion.</p>

  <h2 id="safety">Safety & Quality Standards</h2>

  <div class="alert--warning">
    <h3>Important Safety Considerations</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>No legal recourse:</strong> If you have a problem or dispute inside a club, there's no official authority to appeal to. Clubs self-regulate. Choose places with good reputations.</li>
      <li><strong>Inconsistent testing:</strong> Cannabis is not officially tested in Madrid clubs. Quality and potency vary. You're trusting the club's sourcing and the seller's honesty. Buy small amounts first to test quality.</li>
      <li><strong>Product safety:</strong> Edibles can be unpredictably potent. Hash and concentrates are more potent than flower. Start slowly, especially if you're not experienced.</li>
      <li><strong>Consumption space:</strong> Secondhand smoke is real. Some clubs are better ventilated than others. If you're sensitive or you want to avoid smoke, ask about smoking rooms or outdoor areas.</li>
      <li><strong>Police raids:</strong> Clubs operate in a gray zone. Raids happen, though they're not common. Know your legal status as a foreign national if you're arrested. (Consult a lawyer if you're concerned about this.)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>Madrid cannabis clubs have existed for decades, which suggests they've found a workable equilibrium with authorities. They're not constantly raided like street dealers. But they're not legal either. The risk level is low for members, but it's not zero.</p>

  <p>Quality control is the real issue. Unlike Amsterdam coffee shops, which are inspected and regulated, Madrid clubs have no external oversight. The club itself decides what standards to maintain. Some clubs are fastidious about testing products, rotating stock, and maintaining cleanliness. Others cut corners. You have to do the research and trust your own judgment.</p>

  <p>For tourists, the biggest risk is usually just buying low-quality product or misjudging the potency of an edible. Start conservatively. Ask questions. Watch other people's consumption habits. Take your time before trying something new. The cannabis itself is unlikely to be dangerous—it's not laced with anything sinister—but the potency and your own tolerance are variables you need to manage.</p>

  <p>One more thing: bring cash. Credit cards don't work due to banking complications. Most clubs have ATMs on-site, but the fees are high. Withdraw money before you visit. And keep your membership card and ID on you—you'll need them to enter.</p>

  <p>Madrid's cannabis clubs are fascinating, unique spaces that exist in a legal and cultural middle ground that's hard to find anywhere else. They're not as commercialized as Amsterdam, but they're not as hidden as street dealing. They're social, generally safe for members, and surprisingly professional. If you understand how they work and respect the culture, the experience is genuinely rewarding—not just for the cannabis, but for the access to a part of local life that most tourists never see.</p>
